WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.620 --> 00:00:03.370
GORAN K. HANSSON: The Royal
Swedish Academy of Sciences

00:00:03.370 --> 00:00:08.030
has today decided to award
the Sveriges Riksbank

00:00:08.030 --> 00:00:12.350
Prize in Economic Sciences
in Memory of Alfred Nobel

00:00:12.350 --> 00:00:17.990
to Angus Deaton, for his
analysis of consumption,

00:00:17.990 --> 00:00:19.640
poverty, and welfare.

00:00:22.420 --> 00:00:23.790
ANGUS DEATON:
Looking back on it,

00:00:23.790 --> 00:00:28.480
it seems like a sort of golden
fairytale adventure, in which

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:30.700
it's really hard to
believe it was real,

00:00:30.700 --> 00:00:35.190
even from the first phone
call, when they said what

00:00:35.190 --> 00:00:36.910
they were giving it to me for.

00:00:36.910 --> 00:00:40.930
And I'd always sort
of thought that I

00:00:40.930 --> 00:00:43.050
had relatively low
chance of getting it,

00:00:43.050 --> 00:00:46.160
because they like to say
they're giving it for one big,

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:47.280
deep thing.

00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:50.330
They sort of saw a theme
in this, in terms of it

00:00:50.330 --> 00:00:52.860
all being about welfare
and measurement.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:55.980
There is a theme of that sort,
and that theme has been there

00:00:55.980 --> 00:00:57.080
for a very long time.

00:00:57.080 --> 00:00:59.500
CHRISTOPHER L. EISGRUBER: I
myself first met Angus shortly

00:00:59.500 --> 00:01:01.950
after I joined the Woodrow
Wilson School faculty,

00:01:01.950 --> 00:01:04.970
and was immediately
impressed with his leadership

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:06.920
in the school and
his willingness

00:01:06.920 --> 00:01:09.040
to tackle important questions.

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:11.880
I am thrilled that this
year's Nobel Prize was awarded

00:01:11.880 --> 00:01:14.480
to someone who is
both a great economist

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:16.680
and a great Princetonian.

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:19.500
CECILIA ROUSE: I believe that
Angus Deaton's work and Angus

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:22.010
Deaton is motivated by
public policy in everything

00:01:22.010 --> 00:01:25.470
that he does, whether it's
looking at consumption, income

00:01:25.470 --> 00:01:29.570
inequality, poverty, that he is
motivated to better understand

00:01:29.570 --> 00:01:31.180
the world to make
it a better place.

00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:35.700
ANNE CASE: He brings This
curiosity to the question,

00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:37.930
and has never lost that.

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:40.930
His sense of wonder
about the world

00:01:40.930 --> 00:01:43.650
is, I would say, second to none.

00:01:43.650 --> 00:01:45.900
HENRY FARBER: He is one of
the few economists I really

00:01:45.900 --> 00:01:49.050
want to emulate,
because he's what I

00:01:49.050 --> 00:01:50.380
would call a true intellectual.

00:01:50.380 --> 00:01:52.050
He reads voluminously.

00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:54.060
He reads everything he
can get his hands on.

00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:57.320
So he always has a broad view
of the problem he is working on.

00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:59.810
JANET CURRIE: I think
Angus is one of the people

00:01:59.810 --> 00:02:05.040
that best embodies a traditional
notion that both data

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:07.400
and theory are very important.

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:12.250
ILYANA KUZIEMKO: Angus' style
of research I think of as

00:02:12.250 --> 00:02:15.570
incredibly liberating, to me
as a young assistant professor,

00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:17.110
when I came to Princeton.

00:02:17.110 --> 00:02:20.700
Both Angus and Anne
just made me feel

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:24.100
like I didn't have to
work on one idea, which I

00:02:24.100 --> 00:02:25.670
think is very much Angus' work.

00:02:25.670 --> 00:02:28.540
And I think that's sort of
indicative of the way the Nobel

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:31.130
Prize gave Angus an
award for being Angus.

00:02:31.130 --> 00:02:32.920
CHRISTINA PAXSON: Angus
approaches problems

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:34.620
in a very distinctive way.

00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:37.570
And I guess I would say
he almost approaches them

00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:39.300
like a detective.

00:02:39.300 --> 00:02:41.300
He comes up with a
very interesting,

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:42.320
important question.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:45.620
He wants to find out
the answer to it.

00:02:45.620 --> 00:02:47.910
He doesn't have any
preconceived notions about what

00:02:47.910 --> 00:02:50.150
that answer might be,
and he's as likely

00:02:50.150 --> 00:02:54.850
to find something that is
unexpected as something that's

00:02:54.850 --> 00:02:57.200
expected.

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:59.790
GORAN K. HANSSON: Dear
Professor Deaton, you

00:02:59.790 --> 00:03:04.120
are an optimist, a
skeptic, and a humanist.

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:09.480
And above all, you are an
empiricist, always determined

00:03:09.480 --> 00:03:14.750
to confront what we believe
with what we can know, just

00:03:14.750 --> 00:03:17.400
like Alfred Nobel.

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:20.050
It is an honor and
a privilege for me

00:03:20.050 --> 00:03:23.060
to convey to you, on
behalf of the Royal Swedish

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:27.080
Academy of Sciences, our
warmest congratulations.

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:31.470
May I now please ask you to step
forward and receive your prize

00:03:31.470 --> 00:03:33.250
from His Majesty, the King.

00:03:33.250 --> 00:03:35.680
