00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:46.750
ANGUS DEATON: One of my greatest
pleasures in recent years

00:03:46.750 --> 00:03:50.880
has been seeing the
subject matter of economics

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:53.690
broaden and expand.

00:03:53.690 --> 00:03:58.150
It has not given up its core
themes, its measurement,

00:03:58.150 --> 00:04:03.820
or its mathematics, but it
has re-embraced its origins

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:08.660
in history, in psychology,
and political science,

00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:12.260
in sociology,
and in philosophy.

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:16.370
It has become a richer
and more humane subject.

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:19.520
ORLEY ASHENFELTER: What
probably makes him exceptional--

00:04:19.520 --> 00:04:23.450
and I think maybe the Nobel
committee appreciated--

00:04:23.450 --> 00:04:28.170 position:67%
is that he doesn't leave it
at perfecting or improving economic theory.

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:31.680
He tries to take
that to some data

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:35.480
and use it to explore
the details of what

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:36.520
he's discovered.

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:39.750
ANNE CASE: Angus came
to Princeton in 1983.

00:04:39.750 --> 00:04:43.590
And starting with
that Class of 1983,

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:50.480
he has left an indelible print
on a generation of students who

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:52.690
have come through Princeton.

00:04:52.690 --> 00:04:54.880
He is a terrific lecturer.

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:59.110
He is crystal clear, and he is
really excited about the work.

00:04:59.110 --> 00:05:01.610
And he makes other people
excited about the work.

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:04.550
JANET CURRIE: Angus was one of
my first teachers at Princeton.

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:07.490
So I actually still
remember having

00:05:07.490 --> 00:05:09.620
him walk into the classroom.

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:12.270
And I don't know exactly what
I expected, maybe some little

00:05:12.270 --> 00:05:13.190
wiry Scotsman.

00:05:13.190 --> 00:05:17.230
And this great, huge
bear of a man walked in.

00:05:17.230 --> 00:05:19.310
He was taller than
the blackboard.

00:05:19.310 --> 00:05:21.400
I was really impressed.

00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:23.190
And then of course when
he started to talk,

00:05:23.190 --> 00:05:24.500
I was even more impressed.

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:29.230
He gave an absolutely beautiful
course on econometrics.

00:05:29.230 --> 00:05:34.010
He was one of my advisers
for my dissertation.

00:05:34.010 --> 00:05:36.290
I have known Angus
for a long time.

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:40.330
One characteristic that
stands out, he's very funny.

00:05:40.330 --> 00:05:43.750
He's very knowledgeable
about many subjects.

00:05:43.750 --> 00:05:47.960
If you had to pick one person to
have dinner with and be certain

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:51.530
that you would not be bored,
he would be a very good person

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:52.580
to pick.

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:55.190
ILYANA KUZIEMKO:
Angus the man, well--

00:05:55.190 --> 00:05:56.720
How would I describe Angus?

00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:02.730
Probably best not to
talk to him after a game

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:05.730
in which the Yankees lost
in a close situation.

00:06:05.730 --> 00:06:07.440
HENRY FARBER: Angus
is completely human.

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:10.290
I mean, he doesn't hide much.

00:06:10.290 --> 00:06:12.650
So he lets it all hang out.

00:06:12.650 --> 00:06:14.960
And so that makes
him a good friend,

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:17.410
and just a good person
to be around because

00:06:17.410 --> 00:06:19.460
for a person of
his accomplishment

00:06:19.460 --> 00:06:25.530
to be as natural as he is, to me
is a gift to me, if not to him.

00:06:25.530 --> 00:06:26.990
CHRISTINA PAXSON:
I should tell you

00:06:26.990 --> 00:06:29.790
that I came to Princeton
University because

00:06:29.790 --> 00:06:31.720
of Angus Deaton.

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:36.720
I was a labor economist looking
to turn into a development

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:39.630
economist, and he
was an econometrician

00:06:39.630 --> 00:06:41.920
who hadn't been at Princeton
long who wanted to become

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:44.200
a development economist.

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:50.440
And Angus' offer to me
was, come to Princeton,

00:06:50.440 --> 00:06:53.350
I'm putting together
a group, and we

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:57.960
can do this, become development
economists, together.

00:06:57.960 --> 00:07:02.180
And the span of my
collaboration with Angus

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:04.910
lasted literally decades.

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:09.470
And over that period, we
wrote many papers together,

00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:12.000
some of the papers that I
think are the most fun papers

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:13.890
I ever worked on.

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:17.500
And so he was a colleague,
and he has been a teacher,

00:07:17.500 --> 00:07:20.320
and he's been just
a tremendous friend.

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:22.610
CECILIA ROUSE: One of the great
things about Angus Deaton

00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:26.780
is that he is a great
colleague, he's a great mentor,

00:07:26.780 --> 00:07:28.330
he's a good friend.

00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:30.370
He's just an overall
wonderful person,

00:07:30.370 --> 00:07:33.640
so we couldn't be more thrilled
that the world has finally

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:35.850
recognized, or at least the
Nobel Prize committee has

00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:39.960
finally recognized, not only
his contributions to economics,

00:07:39.960 --> 00:07:42.600
but that this is really
a wonderful scholar who's

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:44.980
contributed to all of our
intellectual thinking,

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:46.480
and to all of us as a community.

00:07:49.780 --> 00:07:52.830
